Oh, *Scotland*. Right. Let's get this over with. Don't expect any enthusiasm.

### Demographics of [Scotland](/Scotland)

The population of Scotland, as of 2019, stood at a rather unremarkable 5,463,300. For context, the population growth rate in 2011 was a sluggish 0.6% per annum, according to that overly earnest 2011 GROS Annual Review. [1] It’s a number, I suppose.

Sprawling across 78,782 square kilometres (which is a rather dramatic 30,418 square miles, if you’re keeping score), Scotland has a population density of 67.2 people per square kilometre. That’s 174 per square mile, for those who prefer their measurements less… continental. The truly fascinating part, if you can call it that, is that roughly 70% of the country's population, a solid 3.5 million souls, are crammed into the [Central Belt](/Central_Belt). This isn't some mystical zone; it's just a swathe of land, stretching northeast to southwest, conveniently located between the major [Scottish cities](/Cities_of_Scotland) of [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh) and [Glasgow](/Glasgow). It also manages to encompass other significant settlements like [Paisley](/Paisley,_Renfrewshire), [Stirling](/Stirling), [Falkirk](/Falkirk), [Perth](/Perth,_Scotland) and [Dundee](/Dundee), all nestled within the [Central Lowlands](/Central_Lowlands) – a full 80% of the population, apparently. Other pockets of humanity can be found along the northeast coast, primarily around [Aberdeen](/Aberdeen) and [Inverness](/Inverness), and on the west coast, near the town of [Ayr](/Ayr). Now, for the desolate bits: the [Scottish Highlands](/Scottish_Highlands) and the [Eilean Siar](/Eilean_Siar) islands boast the lowest population densities, a mere 9 people per square kilometre (or 23 per square mile, if you’re feeling generous). And [Glasgow](/Glasgow)? It has the dubious distinction of the highest population density at 3,289 per square kilometre. [2] Riveting.

Until April 2011, the [General Register Office for Scotland](/General_Register_Office_for_Scotland), under its [Registrar-General for Scotland](/Registrar-General_for_Scotland), was responsible for the dreary task of estimating population figures and recording [births](/Births), [deaths](/Deaths), and [marriages](/Marriages). Then, in a move that likely caused minimal disruption to anyone with actual important things to do, the GROS merged with the [National Archives of Scotland](/National_Archives_of_Scotland) to become the [National Records of Scotland](/National_Records_of_Scotland). This new entity is still obligated, by the [Registration of Births, Deaths and Marriages (Scotland) Act 1965](/Registration_of_Births,_Deaths_and_Marriages_(Scotland)_Act_1965), to present an annual report on demographic trends to the [Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government). Naturally, in coordination with the rest of the [United Kingdom](/United_Kingdom), the National Records for Scotland also oversees the decadal [census](/Census). The latest one, in its infinite thoroughness, occurred in March 2022. [3]

#### Historical population

Population change over time

In the grand tradition of meticulous record-keeping, the United Kingdom has conducted a census every ten years since 1801, with a brief, understandable hiatus in 1941 due to the rather inconvenient [Second World War](/Second_World_War). For the years prior to that, we must rely on the more… artisanal data found in directories and gazetteers. [4] [5] [6]

